&gt; Hey Mattias, sorry to go overboard on the commentary but your
&gt; project got me thinking.  You noted:
&gt; 
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; This program violates a few of the NEAT advantages;
&gt; &gt;  * It doesn&#39;t use species (there&#39;d be not point)
&gt; &gt;  * It doesn&#39;t start minimally (that would be dull)
&gt; &gt;
&gt; 
&gt; I have a feeling starting minimally could still be made pretty
&gt; cool.  The reason is that if you have some kind of vague shape or
&gt; design in mind, you could kind of use the principle of
&gt; complexification to get there.  In other words, you&#39;d first start
&gt; out with really simple base shapes and then as NEAT adds neurons
&gt; progressively elaborate on them.  You could even let the user decide
&gt; exactly when or how often to complexify.  You might even put a
&gt; little number next to each picture representing network complexity.
&gt; That way, a user can consciously protect innovation by giving a
&gt; chance to more complex artists even if their pictures are initially
&gt; a bit off from the simpler ones.  I think a program that lets you
&gt; explore from the simple to the complex on your own could be made
&gt; quite compelling.
